This section got WAY too long, so a common case of simplification that is a little bit more complicated (<a data-href="Complex Rational Equations" href="archive/honors-alg-2/rationals/complex-rational-equations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Complex Rational Equations</a>) is it's own note When a factor is cancelled in a rational function a point is removed from its graph, this is called a hole
Steps&nbsp; Factor the numerator and denominator&nbsp;
State any domain restrictions&nbsp; Denominator cannot equal zero Cancel the common factors&nbsp; Write simplified rational expressions and state the domain restrictions&nbsp; Multiplying and dividing&nbsp;
- Multiplication: factor and cancel out&nbsp;
- Division: the second term can be flipped and the division sign turn into a multiplication one&nbsp; If you see a rational on top of another one rewrite as the first one divided as the second one and follow the steps to simplifying&nbsp; Needs to have a common denominator
If it is different find the LCD and make sure both rationals have it by multiplying the top and the bottom&nbsp; Subtracting is basically the same as adding but with a minus sign&nbsp; Key : distribute the minus sign to each term (numerator is easier)&nbsp;
Additive inverses: a number or term which added to the original number or term will give a sum of zero&nbsp; 2x+5, the additive inverse is -2x-5
If the denominator of on rational number when subtracting and adding is the additive inverse of another, you can just multiply the top and bottom by -1 and the denominators will be the same&nbsp; Tldr Factor the denominators&nbsp; Find the LCD
Multiply each term in the expression by the missing factors need in order to get the LCD&nbsp;
Multiply out numerators and combine like terms&nbsp;
Condense and simplify
